         <abstract>
            <p>This paper discusses the conceptual differences in many of the current averages and carefully defines bias in an average. It indicates why comparison of one average with another over many years does not constitute a proof of bias in an average. Since bias is caused by the interaction of (1) price movements of the split stock, (2) price movements of the unsplit stocks, and (3) the method of split adjustment, the authors explain why bias can be verified only by short-run empirical tests on the average.</p>
          </abstract>
